<section label="whats-a-de">
	<title>What is a Differential Equation?</title>
	<aside component="web"><title><e component="emoji">üéß</e> Listen</title>
		<p><audio component="readings" source="audio/readings/c1/c1-connection-to-algebra.mp3" width="100%" /></p>
	</aside>
				
	<introduction>
		<p>
			In this section, we'll explore what a differential equation is, starting with an analogy, and then moving to a formal definition.
		</p>
	</introduction>

	<paragraphs label="connection-to-algebra">
		<title>Connection to Algebra and Calculus</title>

		<p>
			To learn something new, it helps to connect it to something you already know. So let's begin by linking differential equations to algebra.
		</p>

		<p>
			Suppose you're asked to solve each of the following equations for <m>y</m>:
		</p>

		<me>
			y + 2 = 11, \qquad y + 2t = 11, \qquad y^3 + 2t = 11
		</me>

		<p>
			The goal of algebra is to figure out what number or function goes in place of <m>y</m> to make both sides equal. Instead of guessing, you learned rules for isolating <m>y</m>. If we apply those rules, we get:
		</p>

		<md>
			<mrow> y = 9, \qquad y = 11 - 2t, \qquad y^3 \amp = 11 - 2t </mrow>
			<mrow> y \amp = \left(11 - 2t\right)^{1/3} </mrow>
		</md>

		<p>
			Now suppose you're asked to solve a new equation:
		</p>

		<me>
			y' + 2t = 11
		</me>

		<p>
			As before, we isolate <m>y'</m>, giving:
		</p>

		<me>
			y' = 11 - 2t
		</me>

		<p>
			So what function has a derivative of <m>11 - 2t</m>? In other words, what goes in place of <m>y</m> to make this equation true?
		</p>

		<p>
			From calculus, you might recognize this as an anti-derivative problem. So the solution is:
		</p>

		<me>
		y = \int (11 - 2t)\, dt = 11t - t^2 + C.
		</me>

		<p>
			Believe it or not, you just solved a differential equation using algebra and calculus! Most problems won't be quite that straightforward, but the goal is the same: find a function that fits in place of <m>y</m> and makes the equation true.
		</p>
	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs label="definition">
		<title>Definition</title>
		<aside><title><e component="emoji">üéß</e> Listen</title><p><audio component="readings" source="audio/readings/c1/c1-definition.mp3" width="100%" /></p></aside>

		<p>
			Essentially, a differential equation is any equation where the unknown has a derivative applied to it. Here's the formal definition.
		</p>

		<definition xml:id="def-diff-eq">
			<title>Differential Equation</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					A <term>differential equation (DE)</term> is an equation that involves one or more derivatives of an unknown function.
					If the function depends on a single variable, it's called an <term>ordinary differential equation (ODE)</term>.
					If the function depends on more than one variable, it's called a <term>partial differential equation (PDE)</term>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>
		<aside component="web"><title>DE <m>\Rightarrow</m> ODE</title>
			<p>
				<e component="emoji">üìå</e> Since this course only covers <em>ordinary differential equations</em>,	any time we say <em>differential equation</em> or <em>DE</em>, we mean <em>ODE</em>.
			</p>
		</aside>
	
		<p>
			So, for an equation to qualify as a differential equation, it must include two things:
			First, it needs a derivative‚Äîsomething like <m>f'</m> or <m>\frac{dy}{dx}</m>.
			Second, it must have an equals sign.
		</p>

		<p>
			That means all of the following are differential equations:
		</p>

		<me>
			\frac{dy}{dx} + 1 = y, \qquad f^{\prime\prime} + x^2 + 3x = 19, \qquad e^t = \tan(y^\prime)
		</me>

		<p>
			On the other hand, these are not differential equations‚Äîeither because they don't contain a derivative, or because they don't include an equals sign:
		</p>

		<me>
			\frac{d^2 y}{dx^2} + 2\frac{dy}{dx}, \qquad \sin y + e^x = 0
		</me>

		<exercise label="c1-definition-chkpt-bundle">
			<title><e component="emoji">üìñ‚ùì</e>Differential Equation Definition</title>
			<task label="c1-definition-chkpt-1">
				<title><e component="emoji">üìñ‚ùì</e> Not Required for a DE</title>
				<statement>Which of the following is NOT required for an equation to be classified as a differential equation?</statement>
				<choices randomize="yes">
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement>A <m>y</m>-variable</statement>
						<feedback>Correct! A <m>y</m>-variable is not a requirement for a differential equation.</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>An unknown function</statement>
						<feedback>Incorrect. A differential equation does include an unknown function, which we are solving for.</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>One or more derivatives of an unknown function</statement>
						<feedback>Incorrect. The presence of at least one derivative is essential to define a differential equation.</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>An equal sign, "="</statement>
						<feedback>Incorrect. An equality sign is required for an equation to be classified as a differential equation.</feedback>
					</choice>
				</choices>
			</task>
			<task label="c1-definition-chkpt-2">
				<title><e component="emoji">üìñ‚ùì</e> Identifying the Differential Equation</title>
				<statement>Which of the following equations is a differential equation.</statement>
				<choices randomize="yes">
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement><m>\quad y'' + 1 = y</m></statement>
						<feedback>Correct! This equation involves a derivative, making it a differential equation.</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement><m>\quad x^2 + 3x = 19</m></statement>
						<feedback>Incorrect. This equation does not contain any derivatives, so it is not a differential equation.</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement><m>\quad \sin y + e^x = 0</m></statement>
						<feedback>Incorrect. This equation does not contain any derivatives, so it is not a differential equation.</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement><m>\quad y^2 + 5 = 0</m></statement>
						<feedback>Incorrect. This equation does not contain any derivatives, so it is not a differential equation.</feedback>
					</choice>
				</choices>
			</task>
		</exercise>
	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs label="derivative-notation">
		<title>Common Derivative Notations</title>
		<aside><title><e component="emoji">üéß</e> Listen</title><p><audio component="readings" source="audio/readings/c1/c1-derivative-notation.mp3" width="100%" /></p></aside>

		<p>
			In this text, we'll use several common notations for derivatives. These include prime notation, like <m>y'</m> or <m>y''</m>; Leibniz notation, using <m>\frac{dy}{dx}</m>; and dot notation, which is typically reserved for derivatives with respect to time.
		</p>

		<p>
			<sidebyside widths="12% 62%" margins="10% 16%" valign="middle">
				<p><me>\text{Notation}</me></p>
				<p><me>\text{Derivative Order}</me></p>
			</sidebyside>
			<sidebyside widths="12% 10% 10% 10% 10% 4% 10%" margins="10% 16%" valign="middle">
				<p/>
				<p><me>1\text{st}</me></p>
				<p><me>2\text{nd}</me></p>
				<p><me>3\text{rd}</me></p>
				<p><me>4\text{th}</me></p>
				<p><me>...</me></p>
				<p><me>n\text{th}</me></p>
			</sidebyside>
			<sidebyside widths="12% 10% 10% 10% 10% 4% 10%" margins="10% 16%" valign="middle">
				<p><me>\text{Prime}\vphantom{\frac11}</me></p>
				<p><me>y'</me></p>
				<p><me>y''</me></p>
				<p><me>y'''</me></p>
				<p><me>y^{(4)}</me></p>
				<p><me>...</me></p>
				<p><me>y^{(n)}</me></p>
			</sidebyside>
			<sidebyside widths="12% 10% 10% 10% 10% 4% 10%" margins="10% 16%" valign="middle">
				<p><me>\text{Leibniz}</me></p>
				<p><me>\ds\frac{dy}{dx}</me></p>
				<p><me>\ds\frac{d^2y}{dx^2}</me></p>
				<p><me>\ds\frac{d^3y}{dx^3}</me></p>
				<p><me>\ds\frac{d^4y}{dx^4}</me></p>
				<p><me>...</me></p>
				<p><me>\ds\frac{d^ny}{dx^n}</me></p>
			</sidebyside>
			<sidebyside widths="12% 10% 10% 10% 10% 4% 10%" margins="10% 16%" valign="middle">
				<p><me>\text{Dot}\vphantom{\frac11}</me></p>
				<p><me>\dot{y}</me></p>
				<p><me>\ddot{y}</me></p>
				<p><me>\dddot{y}</me></p>
				<p><me>\ddddot{y}</me></p>
				<p><me>...</me></p>
				<p><me>\text{---}</me></p>
			</sidebyside>
		</p>

		<aside>
			<title>Notation</title>
			<p>
				<e component="emoji">üìå</e> Be careful not to mistake <m>y^{(4)}</m> as <m>y</m> raised to the power of 4.
			</p>
			<p>
				<e component="emoji">üìå</e> Dot notation is normally reserved for derivatives with respect to time.
			</p>
		</aside>

		<exercise label="rq-whats-a-de-2">
			<title><e component="emoji">üìñ‚ùì</e> Understanding Derivative Notation</title>
			<statement>The expression <m>z^{(18)}</m> is the same as <m>z</m> to the power of 18.</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice>
					<statement> True </statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect. Please read the note on derivative notation.</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>False</statement>
					<feedback>Correct!</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
			<feedback>
				
			</feedback>
		</exercise>
	</paragraphs>

